        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Correlator Setup for 0.2'' ALMA observations at 259.0 GHz

In this band we target the J=3-2 transition of H13CN (259.00 GHz) and of HC15N 
(258.15 GHz) in baseband 1, a group of CCH N=3-2 transitions (261.99 GHz) 
transitions in baseband 2, and a continuum measurement in baseband 3. The 
linewidths in this face-on source are of order 1 km/s, setting the desired 
spectral resolution to 0.07 km/s. For CCH, the spectral resolution is set to 
0.14 km/s in order to include all of the CCH lines in one spectral window.

Requested Sensitivity for 0.2'' ALMA observations at 259.0 GHz

Lines from three molecular species and one continuum setting are requested 
within this science goal. Flux from the primary molecular transition, H13CN 
3-2, can be predicted based on the previously detected HCN 3-2 flux 
(Qi et al. 2008). We expect the HCN 3-2 flux to be 0.864 Jy (see Justification 
Text, Goal #1) when smoothed to 0.275 km/s. The abundance of H13CN / HCN matches
13C/12C ~ 1/62. A good estimate of the optical depth of the HCN 3-2 line is ~5, 
then we expect H13CN 3-2 flux to be 0.864 Jy * (1 - exp(-5/62)) = 67 mJy. 
We can smooth our spectral resolution to 0.275.
To achieve a 10 sigma detection, the rms sensitivity should be 6.7 mJy, which 
requires a 1.18 hour observation according to the OT estimate. Even if the HCN 
is optically thin, which is highly unlikely (e.g. Oberg et al. 2010), we will 
detect the H13CN 3-2 flux at 4 sigma by further integrating over velocity.

The continuum flux of 250 mJy is estimated from the ~0.6'' angular resolution
observations of TW Hya at 870 microns by Andrews et al. 2012, ApJ, 744, 162.   
Assuming the flux scales as nu^3 this gives 125 mJy at 1.11 mm.
The surface density generally scales as 1/r with
surface area going as r^2.  Thus we assume the continuum scales with
radius giving ~41 mJy
Thus the expected line rms to continuum is 11.0mJy/41 mJy or 1:4.

Imaging requirements:
As in Science Goal #1, we request observations with two 12m array configurations
to achieve sensitivity to scales of 0.2'' (11 AU) and to the outer disk. The 
high resolution configuration is motivated by a goal of resolving the radial 
abundance and excitation temperature structure of HCN, while the compact 
configuration is to detect emission from the outer disk, which is important for 
making overall abundance measurements.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
