        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Correlator Setup for 0.4'' ALMA observations at 431.7 GHz

In this band we target the J=5-4 transition of three HCN isotopologues: H13CN 
(431.64 GHz) and HC15N (430.24 GHz) in baseband 1, HCN (443.12 GHz) in 
baseband 2, and a continuum measurement in baseband 3. The linewidths in this 
face-on source are of order 1 km/s, setting the desired spectral resolution to 
0.08 km/s.

Requested Sensitivity for 0.4'' ALMA observations at 431.7 GHz

Three molecular lines and one continuum setting are requested within this 
science goal. Our primary driver is the detection of H13CN 5-4, which we
estimate from the previously detected HCN 3-2 flux (Qi et al. 2008). As
before we assume an optical depth of 5 which suggests that H13CN 3-2 line
flux is 67 mJy in 0.2'' beam.   With optically thin emission and an 
excitation temperature of ~30 K (typical for the disk surface) the line 
flux ratio from (5-4)/(3-2) is around 2.7.   Thus our expected flux is 
on the order of 181 mJyin a 0.2'' beam.  Assuming flux scaling with
radius this gives 360 mJy in 0.4'' beam. If HCN is optically thin the predicted
flux would be on the order of 60 mJy.   We propose a sensitivity of 18 mJy 
to guarantee that the H13CN 5-4 line will be detected to above 4sigma 
significance in the worst-case scenario of optically thin HCN, and much more 
if HCN is optically thick. This would take 58.3 minutes according to the OT 
estimate. If HCN 5-4 is optically thick with tau &gt;= 5, then our observation 
should also be sensitive to HC15N 5-4 flux to at least 3 sigma, so we include 
a spectral window centered on the HC15N 5-4 line. The abundance of 
HC15N / HCN matches 15N/14N ~ 1/450. In this tau=5 case, we expect 
HC15N 5-4 flux to be 5.7 * (1 - exp(-5/450)) = 63 mJy. The corresponding 
sensitivity at 0.08 km/s is 28 mJy.

The continuum flux of 400 mJy is estimated from the ~0.6" angular resolution
observations of TW Hya at 870 microns by Andrews et al. 2012, ApJ, 744, 162.  
Assuming the flux scales as nu^3 this gives 625 mJy at  670 um.
The surface density generally scales as 1/r with
surface area going as r^2.  Thus we assume the continuum scales with
radius giving ~400 mJy
Thus the expected line rms to continuum is 11.0mJy/400 mJy or 1:40.

Imaging requirements:
We request observations with a single 12m array configuration to achieve 
sensitivity to scales of 0.4'' (22 AU) and to the outer disk. The configuration 
is motivated by a goal of resolving the radial abundance and excitation 
temperature structure of HCN, while also detecting emission from the outer 
disk, which is important for making overall abundance measurements.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
