    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The delivery of carbon, nitrogen, oxygen, and hydrogen to young terrestrial planets is not well understood. These volatile elements are essential to life on Earth, and so understanding their delivery and chemical evolution is of prime importance to the study of planet formation, astrochemistry, and astrobiology. Abundance measurements of the nitrogen reservoir in the star-forming cloud Orion KL suggest that we can follow the organic N-bearing molecule HCN from the dense ISM to the stage where the analogs of solar system meteorites are forming. We propose ALMA measurements of the abundance of HCN in the nearest protoplanetary disk to the Sun, TW Hydrae, using emission from three HCN isotopologues. With these data, and armed with a gas mass determined by HD, we will be capable of determining the radial abundance distribution and excitation of HCN to search for expected abundance gradients. These observations will allow us to study the evolution of nitrogen-bearing organics from the dense ISM, through the protoplanetary disk stage, to the solar system planetesimals that delivered organic nitrogen to the Earth.</prp:abstract>
